"Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 30 October 2012, Official Report, column 210W, on tobacco: smuggling, how many individual seizures were made by the Border Force and HM Revenue and Customs in each of the last five years; and what the total volume of the products seized in each year was.","false","Biography information for Mark  Spencer","Sherwood","Mark Spencer","9678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418092","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-12","<p>The total spent by HMRC on delivering the Government’s strategy to tackle tobacco smuggling in each of the last five years is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£65.75m</p></td><td><p>£68.92m</p></td><td><p>£67.61m</p></td><td><p>£76.00m</p></td><td><p>£78.001m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Border Force cannot provide the information requested without incurring disproportionate costs.</p><p>Border Force adopts an intelligence led approach to all of its customs activities, including tackling tobacco smuggling so that its multi-functional resources can be deployed as effectively as possible in line with latest threat assessments.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418092/answer",,,,,,"2015-10-12T13:53:11.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418092/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418092/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much (a) the UK Border Force and (b) HM Revenue and Customs spent on delivering the Government's tobacco smuggling strategy in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mark  Spencer","Sherwood","Mark Spencer","9684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418093","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-14","<p>216 of 336 local planning authorities (64%) have adopted and 276 (82%) published a Local Plan. Approximately 59% of England’s land area is covered by adopted Local Plans and 82% covered by published plans. In the Productivity Plan published on 10 July the Government reiterated the importance of a plan-led system and set out the clear expectation that all areas should produce a Local Plan by early 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418093/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T13:46:57.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418093/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418093/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-09","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of land is covered by a local plan.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","9722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418094","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-14","<p>My Department does not collect information on the proportion of land covered by neighbourhood plans. There are now almost 1,500 designated neighbourhood planning areas. 222 local planning authorities in England (66% of the total) include at least one designated neighbourhood planning area. <br><br>We estimate that over 8 million people live within a neighbourhood area, representing around 15% of the population in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418094/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T13:48:51.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418094/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418094/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-09","Neighbourhood Development Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of land is covered by a neighbourhood plan.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","9723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418095","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-14","<p>216 of 336 local planning authorities (64%) have adopted and 276 (82%) published a Local Plan. In its Productivity Plan published on 10 July the Government reiterated the importance of a plan-led system, and set out the clear expectation that all areas should produce a Local Plan by early 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418095/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T13:47:41.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418095/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418095/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-09","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local councils have local plans in place.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","9724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418096","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Government published the report ‘Review of Effectiveness of Local Authority Action Plans (LAQM) and Future Policy Options for LAQM’ in 2013, which looked at a broad selection of local authorities with Air Quality Management Areas that ranged from hotspots to large areas of exceedance. This report concluded that although the review and assessment part of the LAQM regime was working very well, though too bureaucratic, some improvements could also be made to the action planning process.</p><p>We are currently reviewing the Local Air Quality Management system to reduce bureaucracy and enable greater focus on taking action, and intend to consult on a streamlined reporting system and revised guidance later this year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418096/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T13:41:52.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418096/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418096/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-09","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of air quality action plans in tackling local pockets of air pollution.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","9729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418097","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of apprenticeships starts in the Science and Maths Sector Subject Area is published in the FE data library (first link) as a supplementary table (second link) to a Statistical First Release (SFR):</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/438150/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/438150/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418097/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:44:05.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418097/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418097/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Apprentices: STEM Subjects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the level of take-up of mathematics and science apprenticeships so far in 2015.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","9687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418098","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418098/answer","PQ 9692 Paul Blomfield MP.xls ; 9692.pdf","PQ 9692 Paul Blomfield MP.xls ; 9692.pdf","UKSA Attachment for Member - Self-Employment ; UKSA Letter to Member - Self-Employment","UKSA Attachment for Member - Self-Employment ; UKSA Letter to Member - Self-Employment",,"2015-09-15T16:17:35.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418098/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418098/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-09","Self-Employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information his Department holds on levels of self-employment in the (a) construction, (b) care, (c) cleaning, and (d) hospitality sectors.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","9692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418099","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>Following a sale of the Green Investment Bank, remuneration policy will be a matter for the company’s Board and its shareholders.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418099/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T10:20:13.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418099/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418099/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the need to (a) review or (b) increase Green Investment Bank (i) CEO or (ii) board salaries in the event of privatisation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>This Government believes torture is always wrong. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) continues to work with partners and allies to end torture worldwide, we will continue to put the prevention of torture at the heart of our human rights work, as set out in the FCO Strategy for the Prevention of Torture 2011-2015. The FCO is funding projects worth over £700,000 this financial year, focused on practical initiatives to stop torture.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418100/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T12:21:40.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418100/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-09","Torture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when his Department plans to publish the post-2015 strategy for the prevention of torture.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418101","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-24","<p>The Department has engaged with financial investors during the consultation periods, following the announcement on 22 July 2015. We are currently analysing the feedback provided by all stakeholders and will publish the Government’s response in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418101/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-24T11:02:44.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418101/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418101/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Renewable Energy: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to her Department's announcement of 22 July 2015 on renewable energy subsidies, what assessment the Government has made of the effect on international investor confidence in the UK (a) solar and (b) renewable sectors of that announcement; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418102","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-23","<p>A report by BIS, published in March 2015, suggested that in 2013 34,400 people were employed in the wider solar PV sector and its supply chain, although this is likely to include companies that have an involvement in the solar sector without solar being their core business. The BIS report can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416240/bis-15-206-size-and-performance-of-uk-low-carbon-economy.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416240/bis-15-206-size-and-performance-of-uk-low-carbon-economy.pdf</a>.</p><p>Numbers on employment in the sector are not robust enough to show how many jobs are supported directly by either the feed-in tariff (FIT) scheme or the renewables obligation (RO), and for this reason it has not been possible to quantify with a high degree of confidence the impact of proposed changes on employment levels in the sector or the wider economy. We have asked a question in the FIT review consultation about the wider impact of changes.</p><p>Deployment of solar at all levels has been more rapid and more extensive than predicted and this is why we have proposed changes to bring the incentive schemes under greater control and ensure that they provide value for money for electricity bill payers, whilst still supporting deployment.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418102/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-23T12:28:47.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418102/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418102/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Solar Power: Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of announcements on solar policy since May 2015 on (a) current and (b) future employment levels in that sector; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418103","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-16","<p>The estimated number of ISIL fighters killed as a result of UK strikes from September 2014 to 31 August 2015 is around 330. This figure is highly approximate, not least given the absence of UK ground troops in a position to observe the effects of strike activity. We do not believe there have been any civilian casualties as a result of UK strike activity. Any overall estimates would be a matter for the coalition.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418103/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T14:07:37.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418103/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418103/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his letter to the hon. Member for Brighton, Pavilion, dated 24 July 2015, what estimate he has made of the number of ISIL fighters killed as a result of UK strike activity; and what estimate the Global Coalition to Counter ISIL has made of civilian casualties arising from its activities.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418104","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-15","<p>The Justice Secretary told the Justice Select Committee in oral evidence on 17 July that the government would &quot;stick to the government's current practice on consultations&quot;.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418104/answer",,,,,,"2015-10-15T15:21:09.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418104/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418104/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-09","Bill of Rights: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to ensure that civil society and members of the public are able to contribute to a consultation on a British Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418105","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>Since 2014-15 funding to support students in hardship has been incorporated into the Student Opportunities allocation. Information on the Student Opportunities allocations in the 2015-16 academic year is not yet available. Monitoring returns from institutions on the use of the Student Opportunities Fund for the 2014-15 academic year will be submitted to the Higher Education Funding Council (HEFCE) in the first quarter of 2016 and will tell us how what proportion of the Fund was delivered as hardship payments to students. Information for 2015-16 will not be available until the first quarter of 2017.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418105/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T13:45:59.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418105/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418105/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Central Lancashire University","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many students studying at the University of Central Lancashire received hardship grants in the 2015-16 academic year.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","9764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418106","Church Commissioners","false","2015-09-15","<p>The information requested is not held centrally, while there is central guidance available, each Diocese and Parish applies the regulations to their local circumstances. Without more specific information about which parish is being referred to in the question further comment is not further comment is not possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our advice would be to contact the Diocesan Registrar for Blackburn will know how these regulations are applied locally. The Registrar can be contacted at the Diocesan Office:</p><p> </p><p>Church House, Cathedral Close, Blackburn, BB1 5AA</p><p> </p><p>You may also wish to refer to page 4 of the Diocesan guide to the churchyard regulations available at the following link. <br>This document gives the general advice for the Diocese of Blackburn.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.blackburn.anglican.org/images/Information/Churchyard%20Regulations%202014.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.blackburn.anglican.org/images/Information/Churchyard%20Regulations%202014.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418106/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T12:43:52.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418106/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418106/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2015-09-09","Cemeteries","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, which Church of England dioceses have published regulations on monuments on burial plots and inscriptions on gravestones; which dioceses (a) allow and (b) do not allow nicknames on gravestones; which dioceses allow monuments; which dioceses (i) allow and (ii) do not allow pictorial etchings on gravestones; and which dioceses (A) allow and (B) do not allow free-standing containers on burial plots.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","9765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418107","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-14","<p>One hundred and seven projects are in development this financial year. The locations of these projects are shown in the published flood and coastal erosion risk management investment programme 2015 – 2021:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/programme-of-flood-and-coastal-erosion-risk-management-schemes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/programme-of-flood-and-coastal-erosion-risk-management-schemes</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency has reported that between 1 April and 30 June 2015, 19 projects started construction in East England, East Midlands, North West, South East, South West and Yorkshire and Humber Office of National Statistics (ONS) regions and 26 projects completed construction in East England, East Midlands, North West, South East, South West, West Midlands and Yorkshire and Humber ONS regions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>One project in the Environment Agency’s national priority programme reported delays. The start of work on Jacks Key Reservoir, Darwen was delayed due to detailed site investigation showing that the project is more complex than originally anticipated. Construction is now expected to start on site in early 2016.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418107/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T10:12:16.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418107/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418107/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-09","Coastal Erosion and Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to page 16 of Reducing the risks of flooding and coastal erosion: An investment plan, published by her Department in December 2014, what progress the Environment Agency has reported on the number and location of projects starting in development, construction and completing as well as the reasons for delay.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","9766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418108","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-14","<p>No decision has been made on the future of Ormskirk Magistrates Court. Access to justice is not just about proximity to a court. To ensure that access to justice is maintained, we are committed to providing alternative ways for users to access our services, including the use of other civic buildings.</p><p> </p><p>No decisions will be made until every response to the current consultation has been considered carefully.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418108/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T16:53:24.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418108/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418108/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-09","Magistrates' Courts: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effects of the proposed closure of Ormskirk Magistrates' Court on the (a) costs and (b) length of journeys to Preston Magistrates' Court for people from Skelmersdale, Halsall, Scarisbrick and other parts of West Lancashire who rely on public transport; and what assessment he has made of the effect on Preston Magistrates' Court of the length and complexity of journeys on public transport by defendants.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","9767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418109","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-14","<p>This information is not available.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418109/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T13:49:48.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418109/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418109/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-09","Local Enterprise Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many representations his Department has received from (a) councillors, (b) hon. Members and (c) members of the public expressing concerns over the working of local enterprise partnerships in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","9825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418110","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government does not currently plan to extend the Freedom of Information Act to Local Enterprise Partnerships.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418110/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T16:46:44.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418110/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418110/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-09","Freedom of Information: Local Enterprise Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department plans to extend freedom of information to local enterprise partnerships.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","9826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418111","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-17","<p>This is a matter for the Money Advice Service who have agreed to write in response to the honourable gentleman.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418111/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T10:25:40.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418111/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418111/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Money Advice Service: Contracts for Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what date the tender which led to the Money Advice Service finding 100 new debt advisers posts at Stepchange was published; how many and who the shortlisted bidders were for that tender; on what date the decision on the tender was made; and if he will publish in full information on to how that tendering process was undertaken.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","9818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418112","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is expected to directly spend approximately £1.3billion on low carbon innovation (research development and demonstration) in this spending review period (2011-15). This support is coordinated through the Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group<sup>1</sup> (LCICG).</p><p>Support beyond the end of this financial year is dependent on the outcome of the Spending Review.</p><p><em><sup>1</sup> <a href="http://www.lowcarboninnovation.co.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.lowcarboninnovation.co.uk/</a>.</em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418112/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:28:15.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418112/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418112/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what support the Government is providing for early stage innovation in the low carbon sector.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","9797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418113","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-14","<p>Defra followed normal practice for developing the Hunting Act 2004 (Exempt Hunting) (Amendment) Order 2015. Defra has received representations from a number of organisations about the repeal of the Hunting Act 2004. It received no representations from the Countryside Alliance on the Hunting Act 2004 (Exempt Hunting) (Amendment) Order 2015 prior to its publication.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418113/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:32:53.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418113/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418113/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-09","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department showed the Countryside Alliance the Hunting Act 2004 (Exempt Hunting) (Amendment) Order 2015 in draft prior to publication; and what representations she received from that organisation on the matters covered by that Order prior to its publication.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","9715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418114","Home Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>Fourteen Chinese nationals and eight Vietnamese nationals were removed to the Hook of Holland. The remaining 46 individuals - comprising Afghan (35), Chinese (8), Vietnamese (2) and Russian (1) nationality - have claimed asylum and are being processed within the asylum system. If their claims are not substantiated they will be expected to leave the UK, or will be forcibly removed. The four lorry drivers were arrested and bailed and are due to answer bail in November.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418114/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T14:10:32.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418114/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-09","Illegal Immigrants: Harwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, where each of the (a) 68 clandestine migrants and (b) four lorry drivers are that were stopped in Harwich in June 2015; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","9820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418115","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>People who think they have contracted hepatitis C via National Health Service-supplied blood or blood products should contact their general practitioner in the first instance and also the Skipton Fund, one of the ex-gratia payment schemes offering support to those affected by this tragedy.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418115/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T14:44:15.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418115/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418115/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-09","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department provides to people diagnosed with hepatitis C acquired through NHS blood treatments where medical records have been lost.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","9702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418116","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-15","<p>The 2013/14 Renewables Obligation sustainability data [1] indicate that, for data available, the average greenhouse gas saving from energy crops on the European Union fossil fuel electricity average, by consignment, was approximately 90% (within a range of 85-94%). Feedstock data will begin being collected for Renewable Heat Incentive from the beginning of October, but energy crops are expected to make up a small proportion of heat biomass feedstock.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As recommended in the Bioenergy Strategy, this year the UK government is introducing mandatory sustainability criteria for biomass supported under the Renewables Obligation and the Renewable Heat Incentive. This will ensure that bioenergy feedstock is from sustainable land types, and that feedstock must meet a minimum 60% greenhouse gas saving on the EU fossil fuel electricity average. These requirements apply to energy crops.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/publications-and-updates/biomass-sustainability-dataset-2013-14" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/publications-and-updates/biomass-sustainability-dataset-2013-14</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418116/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T16:40:19.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418116/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418116/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418116/answer/previousversion/21296","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Biofuels: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of biomass energy crops in delivering carbon reductions as set out in the UK Bioenergy Strategy.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418117","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave the hon. Member for Greenwich and Woolwich on 6 June 2015 to Question 4832:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-30/4832/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-30/4832/</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418117/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:22:48.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418117/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418117/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Renewable Energy: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent assessment her Department has made of the capacity of the UK to meet the 20 per cent renewable target for 2020 set out in the EU Renewable Energy Directive.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418118","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-15","<p>Solar and wind have received support over the past five years from the Renewables Obligation (RO) and the Feed-in Tariff (FITs) schemes. The cost of the schemes is reclaimed from electricity consumers, not from general taxation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The cost of supporting solar and wind through the RO in 2010/11 to 2014/15 was as follows (figures not adjusted for inflation):</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Onshore wind</strong></p></td><td><p>£398m</p></td><td><p>£483m</p></td><td><p>£557m</p></td><td><p>£756m</p></td><td><p>£787m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Offshore wind</strong></p></td><td><p>£254m</p></td><td><p>£371m</p></td><td><p>£699m</p></td><td><p>£989m</p></td><td><p>£1,108m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Solar PV</strong></p></td><td><p>£0.2m</p></td><td><p>£0.1m</p></td><td><p>£0.9m</p></td><td><p>£35m</p></td><td><p>£134m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Solar and some small-scale onshore wind are also supported by the FIT, but FIT costs are not available disaggregated by technology. Total support under FiT in 2013/14 (the latest year for which data are available) was £691m.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418118/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T16:42:45.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418118/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418118/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418118/answer/previousversion/21293","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Renewable Energy: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate her Department has made of the cost to the public purse of subsidies paid to the (a) solar and (b) wind power industries in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418119","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-15","<p>The previous government supported the Energy Crop Scheme which provided a five year subsidy support for farmers and landowners producing biomass for electricity and heat production. This scheme, which provided support for planting and developing new energy crops, closed on 31<sup>st</sup> August 2013 to new applicants but continues to support those still in the scheme. The payments in the last five years were estimated by Natural England to be:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>2010 – £425,942</li><li>2011 – £594,698</li><li>2012 – £1,320,813</li><li>2013 – £427,198</li><li>2014 – £330,438</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Natural England, who run the scheme, estimate that 80% of the energy crops planted under the scheme will eventually be harvested for power generation, the remainder being for heat generation.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418119/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T16:42:13.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418119/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418119/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418119/answer/previousversion/21294","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Biofuels: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate her Department has made of the total subsidy paid for biomass production for the purposes of power generation in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418120","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-15","<p>DECC holds data, obtained from HMRC, on the imports of fuel wood products, including: wood, wood pellets, wood chips, sawdust and wood waste. The vast majority of wood pellets are used for the purpose of electricity generation in large biomass plants. However, this may not be the case for other fuel wood products. This is summarised in the table below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Value of imports (£million)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wood pellets</p></td><td><p>68</p></td><td><p>129</p></td><td><p>185</p></td><td><p>412</p></td><td><p>545</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other fuel wood products (wood, wood chips, sawdust, wood waste)</p></td><td> </td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All fuel wood products</p></td><td><p>68</p></td><td><p>138</p></td><td><p>195</p></td><td><p>425</p></td><td><p>560</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418120/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T16:41:28.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418120/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418120/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418120/answer/previousversion/21295","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Biofuels: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate her Department has made of the value of biomass imported for the purposes of power generation in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418121","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>Yes.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418121/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:46:02.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418121/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418121/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Ministry of Defence: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2015 to Question 5988, whether his Department operates a licensing system for trial hunting on its land.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","9790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418122","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>All forms of exempt hunting, in line with the Hunting Act, are permissible on Ministry of Defence land, subject to it being compatible with the Defence use, that the Department is satisfied the proposed activity constitutes exempt hunting and that there is a requirement for it.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418122/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:56:16.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418122/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418122/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Ministry of Defence: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2015 to Question 5988, whether his Department permits hunting exempt under Schedule 1 of the Hunting Act 2004 on its land.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","9690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418123","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>The number of complaints received from ex-Service personnel about the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme could be provided only at disproportionate cost as each complaint would need to be examined to determine if the individual was ex-Service, and their complaint was about the Scheme rather than their personal award.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 11 September 2015 to Question 9008 to the hon. Member for Bridgend (Madeleine Moon). Between 6 April 2005, and 31 March 2015, (the latest data currently available) 1,345 former Service personnel registered an additional or exceptional claim, reconsideration or appeal following an initial compensation award under the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme.</p><p>In addition between 1 April 2014 and 31 March 2015, the Veterans UK customer service team received a total of 41 complaints relating to the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme.</p><p>From 1 April 2010 the (earliest date data is available) to 31 March 2015, I received a total of 158 letters from MPs on behalf of their constituents, for which the subject matter was the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme. However, this correspondence cannot be broken down in to Serving or ex-Serving personnel, nor can it be broken down by correspondence type such as complaint, claim or enquiry.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418123/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:47:44.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418123/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418123/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Armed Forces Compensation Scheme: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many complaints his Department has received from ex-service personnel about the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","9727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418124","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>Yes.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418124/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:48:19.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418124/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418124/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Ministry of Defence: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2015 to Question 5988, whether any live quarry has been killed during a trail hunt on his Department's land.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","9728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418125","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>Since 2005, some £521 million has been paid under the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme; 80 lump sum payments have been of £570,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418125/answer",,,,,"9007 ; 9769","2015-09-14T15:45:31.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418125/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418125/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Armed Forces Compensation Scheme: Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many awards of £570,000 his Department paid out under their Armed Forces Compensation Scheme since it was established.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","9768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418126","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>Since 2005, some £521 million has been paid under the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme; 80 lump sum payments have been of £570,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418126/answer",,,,,"9007 ; 9768","2015-09-14T15:45:32.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418126/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418126/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-09","Armed Forces Compensation Scheme: Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the amount paid out in awards from the the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme is since it was established in April 2005.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","9769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418127","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department for Transport does not pay its employees through payroll companies or personal services companies.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418127/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T13:37:23.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418127/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418127/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-09","Income Tax: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the payment of salaries through (a) payroll companies and (b) personal service companies to staff who work on projects that are part-funded by his Department.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","9663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418128","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-14","<p>Dame Colette has provided officials with initial draft advice to enable planning of the Department’s response to and implementation of her recommendations. The Secretary of State expects to receive Dame Colette’s final report shortly and as already stated it will be published in the Autumn. Upon publication I will ensure a copy is placed in both Libraries.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418128/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:21:17.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418128/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418128/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-09","Railways: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Dame Colette Bowe has submitted a draft of her report on the planning of major projects to his Department.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","9673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418129","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-14","<p>The network licence issued by ORR sets legally-binding conditions for the licence holder – Network Rail. Condition 1.10 states that:</p><p> </p><p>&quot;the licence holder shall prepare, provide to ORR and publish a delivery plan setting out what the licence holder proposes to do to comply with the general duty in condition 1.2.&quot;</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Network Rail fulfilled this requirement when it published a Delivery Plan for Control Period 5 on 31 March 2014. The Business Plan is distinct from the Delivery Plan and its publication is not a network licence condition.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418129/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T13:43:54.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418129/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418129/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-09","Network Rail: Business Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the publication by Network Rail of a CP5 Business Plan update in March 2015 was a regulated output of Control Period 5.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","9674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418130","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-14","<p>Kettering to Corby which is part 4 and part 2 tracking is currently in full implementation. Bedford to Kettering, in common with all rail projects, is subject to the recommendations of the Hendy Review which is due to report to the Secretary of State for Transport in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418130/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:08:17.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418130/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418130/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-09","Midland Main Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the four-tracking of the Midland Main Line from Bedford to Kettering and Corby is contingent upon the recommendations of the Hendy Review.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","9751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418131","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-14","<p>A number of measures are being put in place including the provision of secure fencing, increased security sweeps and extra security staff for the Fréthun freight yard. The fencing and extra security staff have been financed by HMG. There has also been support for the rail freight operators in the form of regular liaison meetings between the operators, Eurotunnel and Government which has facilitated operational measures such as daytime running at preferential rates.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418131/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T14:33:23.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418131/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418131/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-09","Channel Tunnel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what support he has provided to rail freight operators as a result of the recent disruption to Channel Tunnel services.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","9750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418132","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-28","<p>The UK has corporate criminal liability and commercial organisations can be, and are, prosecuted for wrongdoing. The UK Anti-Corruption Plan tasked the Ministry of Justice to examine the case for a new offence of a corporate failure to prevent economic crime and the rules on establishing corporate criminal liability more widely. Ministers have decided not to carry out further work at this stage as there have been no prosecutions under the model Bribery Act offence and there is little evidence of corporate economic wrongdoing going unpunished.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418132/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-28T10:46:11.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418132/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418132/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-09","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress he has made on Action 36 of the UK Anti-Corruption Plan; and when he expects corporate criminal liability to be introduced.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Gower","Gower","Byron Davies","9735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418133","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-16","<p>World Trade Organization (WTO) Trade in Services negotiations are ongoing and my Department has not carried out such an assessment.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418133/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T13:11:30.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418133/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418133/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-09","Trade in Services Agreement: Fossil Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the Trade in Services Agreement on the domestic oil and gas industry; and when her Department plans to update that assessment.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418134","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA) does not directly cover the laws which underpin workers’ rights in its agreement. The UK Government work closely with the Commission and the <a title="Links to an external resource" href="http://www.ilo.org/global/lang--en/index.htm" target="_blank">International Labour Organisation</a> to ensure that fundamental workers' rights are respected in the context of trade and economic expansion.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418134/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:19:36.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418134/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418134/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Trade in Services Agreement: Industrial Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he has taken in negotiations of the Trade in Services Agreement to ensure that workers' rights are protected.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418135","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA) does not directly cover employment, trade union or company law and no amendments are expected in these areas.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418135/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T12:20:27.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418135/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418135/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he expects the Trade in Services Agreement to entail amendments to (a) employment law, (b) trade union law and (c) company law in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418136","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p /> <p>It is not possible at this stage in the negotiation for the Government to assess the precise impact the TiSA will have on employment levels in the UK economy, but we estimate the agreement has the potential to provide a £2-3 billion increase to the UK’s annual GDP with associated employment gains.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418136/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T15:49:25.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418136/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418136/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Trade Agreements: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the Trade in Services Agreement on employment levels in the UK (a) economy and (b) transport industry.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418137","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>Employment law and trade union rights are not directly included within the TiSA negotiation. The UK government remains strongly committed to the fundamental principles and basic rights for workers arising from the International Labour Organisation (ILO).</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418137/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T12:23:19.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418137/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418137/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Trade in Services Agreement: Industrial Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his policy is on the inclusion of (a) employment law and (b) trades union rights in the Trade in Services Agreement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418138","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA) will not directly cover employment laws or trade union rights. The UK Government works closely with the Commission and the <a title="Links to an external resource" href="http://www.ilo.org/global/lang--en/index.htm" target="_blank">International Labour Organisation</a> to ensure that employment law is respected in the context of trade and economic expansion.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418138/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:16:47.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418138/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418138/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Trade in Services Agreement: Industrial Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment has been made of the potential effect that the Trade in Services Agreement will have on (a) employment law and (b) trade union rights; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418139","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>It is not possible at this stage in the negotiation for the Government to assess the precise sectoral impact of the Trade in Services Agreement, but the European Commission are currently undertaking an impact assessment on the overall impact of the agreement. <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/policy-making/analysis/sustainability-impact-assessments/assessments/" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/policy-making/analysis/sustainability-impact-assessments/assessments/</a></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418139/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T15:49:54.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418139/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418139/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Trade in Services Agreement: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he made of the potential effect of the Trade in Services Agreement on the transport industry; and when his Department plans to update that assessment.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418140","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>In 2014 the Life Science industry generated a trade deficit of £5.0bn for the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Life Sciences goods that can be identified through standard industry classifications consists of pharmaceuticals, irradiation, electro-medical and electrotherapeutic equipment and medical and dental supplies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Recent changes to international legislation on the compilation of the Balance of Payments have classed the trade in illegal drugs as pharmaceuticals. This change accounted for £4.3bn of the imports of pharmaceuticals in 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Comparable figures for Scotland alone are not available.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418140/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T15:28:27.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418140/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418140/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Balance of Trade: Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the life sciences industry generated in trade surplus for (a) the UK and (b) Scotland in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418141","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>Overall, the OBR believes the impact of the restriction to tax relief for finance costs on the housing market will be small and, taking account of the other measures in the Summer Budget, have not adjusted their forecast for house prices.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418141/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:02:59.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418141/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418141/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of the measures to restrict finance cost relief for landlords, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, on the level of housing demand in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418142","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>HM Treasury expects a minimal impact on the supply of property in the private rented sector in Scotland and the UK from changes to restrict tax relief on finance costs. Fewer than 1 in 5 landlords are expected to pay more tax as a result of this measure and it will be introduced gradually from April 2017 over 4 years to give landlords time to adjust. The Budget also announced increased Rent a Room relief, which can help to increase levels of private rented accommodation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is taking significant steps to support housing supply with housing starts at a 7 year high. Overall, the OBR believe the impact on the housing market will be small and, taking account of the other measures in the Summer Budget, have not adjusted their forecast for house prices.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418142/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:05:02.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418142/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418142/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of the measures to restrict finance cost relief for landlords, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, on the supply of property in the private rented sector in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418143","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-17","<p>As part of the Scotland Act 2012 the Government agreed that the Scottish Government would be able to borrow up to a limit of £2.2 billion for capital investment. The Scottish Government is able to borrow for this purpose by any means, including from the Government, private markets, or the issuing of bonds. The current Scotland Bill will be underpinned by a new fiscal framework, allowing the new powers in the Bill to be used effectively. Ministers have committed to agreeing the framework in the autumn and a final agreement will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418143/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T15:05:14.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418143/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418143/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Fiscal Policy: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with Ministers in the Scottish Government on (a) Scottish Government borrowing by means of (i) the National Loans Fund, (ii) private financial institutions and (iii) the issuing of Scottish Government bonds and (b) Scotland's Fiscal Framework in general.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418144","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>The overall cost of housing benefit is dependent on a number of factors such as, household and individual circumstances in regards to employment and household income, inflation and rents. The Government does not expect a large impact on rent levels in Scotland and the UK from this policy, and any impact would be dampened in the short term due to other policy decisions. Therefore the government does not anticipate changes to the overall cost of Housing Benefit as a result.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418144/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:06:11.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418144/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418144/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effects of the measures to restrict finance cost relief for landlords, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, on the overall costs of Housing Benefit in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418145","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government expects the restriction to tax relief for finance costs to have a minimal impact on house building in Scotland and the UK. The Productivity Plan published alongside the Summer Budget includes a number of measures to make the planning system quicker, cheaper and more responsive to local needs. Overall, the OBR believe the impact on the housing market will be small and, taking account of the other measures in the Summer Budget, have not adjusted their forecast for house prices.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418145/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:10:59.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418145/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418145/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of the measures to restrict finance cost relief for landlords, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, on levels of investment in the private rented sector in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418146","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government does not expect the restriction to tax relief for finance costs to have a large impact on rent levels in Scotland or the UK due to the small overall proportion of the housing market affected. There are 1.6 million buy to let mortgages outstanding in the UK overall, out of a total private rented sector of 4.4 million households and total housing stock of 22.6 million households in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418146/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:18:41.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418146/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418146/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of the measures to restrict finance cost relief for landlords, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, on the average rent payable in the private rented sector in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418147","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Scottish Government’s decision to pre-announce the rates and thresholds for the land and buildings transactions tax (LBTT) led to changes in the timing of some transactions in Scotland. Specifically, some higher value transactions were brought forward into 2014-15, while some lower value transactions were delayed into 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In their March 2015 ‘Devolved taxes forecast’ publication, the OBR estimated that <em>“This increases UK SDLT receipts under the old system by £11 million in 2014-15 and reduces the LBTT forecast by £20 million in 2015-16”</em>. The treatment of these policy ‘spillover’ effects was considered by the Smith Commission and is now being discussed by the UK Government and Scottish Government as part of the wider fiscal framework discussions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418147/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:07:31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418147/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418147/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-09","Taxation: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the public purse of forestalling in relation to the land and building transaction tax; and what additional sums the Scottish Government has requested in transfer to the Scottish Budget for 2015-16 in relation to that tax.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418225","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-15","<p>The sugar regime is one of the most heavily regulated and distorting elements of the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP). The agreement, as part of the 2013 reforms, to end sugar beet quotas in 2017 is an important step towards removing these distortions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>During negotiations of the reforms the UK Government argued for a fair and balanced outcome for all parts of the sugar industry. Disappointingly, there was insufficient support from other Member States to secure the necessary changes on imports to allow the cane sector to compete on a level playing field with the beet sector. However, we remain committed to working with the European Commission to address this issue through forthcoming EU trade agreements.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418225/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T09:52:20.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418225/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418225/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-09","Sugar: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to mitigate the effect of recent changes in EU policy on the sugar industry.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","901326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418243","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-15","<p>An estimate of the annual cost to businesses due to inconsistent broadband coverage would quickly be out of date given the rate at which superfast broadband coverage is being extended. Under the government-funded broadband programmes each week we continue to see a further 40,000 premises able to access superfast broadband speeds. Through government investment of over £780 million, superfast broadband is available to over 80% of homes and businesses in the UK compared to 45% in 2010 and by the end of 2017 it will be available to 95% of homes and businesses.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418243/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T15:59:03.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418243/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418243/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-09","Broadband: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the annual cost to businesses of inconsistent broadband coverage.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","901327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418286","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-15","<p>An estimate of the annual cost to businesses due to inconsistent broadband coverage would quickly be out of date given the rate at which superfast broadband coverage is being extended. Under the government-funded broadband programmes each week we continue to see a further 40,000 premises able to access superfast broadband speeds. Through government investment of over £780 million, superfast broadband is available to over 80% of homes and businesses in the UK compared to 45% in 2010 and by the end of 2017 it will be available to 95% of homes and businesses.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418286/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T15:59:47.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418286/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418286/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-09","Broadband: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the annual cost to businesses of inconsistent broadband coverage.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","901342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418767","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>This Government is committed to making sure everyone is paid fairly. I am concerned by recent reports, suggesting some restaurants pocket tips for themselves. That is just not right. I have therefore ordered an investigation into tipping abuse, which closes on 10 November.</p><p> </p>","Bromsgrove","Sajid Javid","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418767/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T16:12:27.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418767/answer","Biography information for Sajid Javid","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418767/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Gratuities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure employers fairly collect and distribute tips left by customers.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","901340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418768","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2015-09-15","<p><del class="ministerial">Apprenticeships are the best form of further education, and we will fund as many as we can. Beyond that we target funding on those who most need help: people of all ages without English and maths, young adults to achieve level 2 or level 3 qualifications, and unemployed people who need help to get a job.</del></p><p><br /><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Nearly 3 million low-paid people will directly benefit from the National Living Wage from April next year. A full-time worker on the current National Minimum Wage will be made £1,200 better off, per year, as a result. Our long-term economic plan is working and we will ensure that the hard work of the British people is recognised through our new National Living Wage.</ins></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418768/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T15:38:22.647Z","2015-09-15T15:48:20.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418768/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418768/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418768/answer/previousversion/21539","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to support people on low pay.","false","Biography information for Matt Warman","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman","901341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418769","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>Apprenticeships are the best form of further education, and we will fund as many as we can. Beyond that we target funding on those who most need help: people of all ages without English and maths, young adults to achieve level 2 or level 3 qualifications, and unemployed people who need help to get a job.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418769/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T15:46:17.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418769/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418769/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of changes in funding for further education on young people.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","901344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418770","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>There have not been any recent discussions with Ministers in the Welsh Government about economic development in the Deeside area.</p><p> </p>","Bromsgrove","Sajid Javid","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418770/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T15:54:27.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418770/answer","Biography information for Sajid Javid","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418770/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-09","Industrial Development: Deeside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with Ministers in the Welsh Government on economic development in the Deeside area.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","901324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417452","Home Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>Professor Hucklesby submitted her findings as part of the public consultation launched by my Right Honourable Friend the Home Secretary in December last year. Officials have been in contact with Professor Hucklesby and have arranged for her to address the next meeting of the PACE Strategy Board in October.</p><p>Professor Hucklesby’s findings are broadly supportive of the reforms to pre-charge bail which the Home Secretary set out in response to the consultation in March of this year. Legislation to give effect to those reforms will be brought forward in the Policing and Criminal Justice Bill later this year.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417452/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T14:37:19.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417452/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417452/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Bail","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the findings by Professor Hucklesby of Leeds University on pre-charge bail; and what action, if any, they plan to take in response to those findings.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417453","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-15","<p>We made a commitment in the Summer Budget to reduce social rents in England by one per cent a year for four years from April 2016. This will help protect tenants from rising housing costs whilst protecting taxpayers from the rising costs of subsidising rents through housing benefit. We are confident that local authorities and private registered providers will be able to find and make efficiencies to accommodate the new rent settlement while meeting their Decent Homes responsibilities. The Government remains committed to delivering 275,000 affordable homes over the course of this Parliament.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417453/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T11:20:06.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417453/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417453/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-08","Council Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the decision to cut social housing rents on the maintenance of existing council housing stock and the number of new council houses likely to be built in the short, medium, and long term.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417454","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>We have made no assessment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The joint National Health Service and National Offender Management Service (NOMS) Offender Personality Disorder (OPD) programme provides a pathway of psychologically informed services for offenders who have a severe personality disorder and who pose a high risk of harm to others or a high risk of reoffending in a harmful way.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The programme has developed a range of services to improve the assessment, treatment and management of this group of offenders from sentence through custody to community-based supervision and resettlement. The NHS is re-investing up to £30 million in OPD services in 2015-16, mainly in prisons and probation services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In response to the objective in the Government’s Mandate to NHS England to provide better healthcare across for people in the criminal justice system in England, including improved mental health care, NHS England has introduced a range of measures to improve mainstream mental health services in prisons.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s new national specifications for health and justice services will help to promote effective and coordinated mental health services across the prison estate in England. All 116 prison establishments now have clear commissioning strategies to improve service delivery.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also developed new performance indicators for prison healthcare with NOMS. These Health and Justice Indicators of Performance will provide assurance that healthcare delivery in prisons, including mental health care, is fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Options for a new mental health pathway, connecting custody, community, as well as secure hospitals, are also being developed to ensure that any prisoner can have mental health treatment equivalent to that they would receive in the community, and that this is also available during a community sentence and after prison.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417454/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T13:50:03.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417454/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417454/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Mental Illness: Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the Oxford University study <i>Psychiatric disorders and violent reoffending: a national cohort study of convicted prisoners in Sweden</i>, and whether they have plans to improve the current level of diagnosis of and treatment provided to prisoners with mental health problems before their release.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417455","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p>Since 2010 the Criminal Cases Review Commission’s budget has been reduced in real terms by 26%. Since 2010, the Commission has improved its performance, closing 947 cases in 2010/11 and 1,632 cases in 2014/15.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417455/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T15:08:23.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417455/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417455/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Criminal Cases Review Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government by how much in real terms funding for the Criminal Cases Review Commission has been cut since 2010; and what assessment they have made of the impact of such a reduction on the working of the Commission.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417456","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-17","<p>DCLG, in conjunction with the tourism sector and the Chief Fire Officers’ Association, has produced guidance to help small-scale accommodation providers comply with the Order’s provisions and Airbnb make this available to hosts on its website.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417456/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T15:58:28.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417456/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417456/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-08","Holiday Accommodation: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the case for extending to properties subject to short or holiday lets, such as those via Air BnB, safety provisions such as those set out in the draft Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm (England) Regulations 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417457","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK has a proud record of leadership on the humanitarian response to the Syria crisis, having pledged a total of £1 billion. The UK has provided over £169 million to the UN World Food Programme (WFP) since the start of the crisis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>WFP, like all our partners, is under intense pressure to respond to massive needs in the region and has had to make some tough choices. The UK strongly supports WFP’s efforts to target the most vulnerable in this crisis, particularly women and children. The UK is closely monitoring the situation across the region, alongside other key donors, to understand how this reduction in support will impact the lives of Syrian refugees.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK does not lobby other donors on behalf of any specific agency, but to focus their attention and their resources on supporting the overall Syria crisis response. The UK is by far the largest bilateral donor in Europe, and second only to the United States, to the Syria crisis. However the UK, the US and the European Union cannot do this alone and other donors must do more to support the needs of millions of Syrians across the region.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417457/answer",,,,,"HL2054 ; HL2055","2015-09-18T12:00:16.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417457/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417457/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-08","World Food Programme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the European Union, the United States of America and other development partners, about the funding of the UN World Food Programme in the light of budgetary pressures ensuing from the refugee crisis in Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Boateng",,"Lord Boateng","HL2053"
