"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417467","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Department does not hold information in the format requested. Figures on closures, mergers and takeovers are collected in total, but are not separable.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417467/answer",,,,,"HL2062","2015-09-21T15:24:45.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417467/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417467/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","General Practitioners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many GP practices have been merged or taken over in (1) England, and (2) London, since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417468","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Referral to treatment waiting times data, which measure waiting times from referral to the start of consultant-led treatment for non-urgent conditions, does not distinguish between patients waiting for surgery and patients waiting for other types of consultant-led treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At the end of July 2015 there were 232,424 people waiting more than 18 weeks to start consultant led treatment compared to 209,411 in May 2010, an increase of 23,013 people. The main driver for this increase is the growth in demand for elective care over the period due to a range of demographic and other factors such as technological changes in the provision of care. However, the number of people waiting more than 18 weeks as a proportion of the total number of people waiting to start consultant-led treatment is lower in July 2015 than in May 2010, 7.1% of the total waiting list compared to 8.1% in May 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The average median waiting times for all patients who started treatment and that involved an admission during July 2015 was 9.1 weeks compared to 8.4 weeks in May 2010. The time waited for those patients who had waited more than 18 weeks to start treatment is not separately identified.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417468/answer",,,,,"HL2065","2015-09-16T13:52:13.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417468/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417468/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Surgery: Waiting Lists","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why, and by how many, the number of people waiting longer than 18 weeks for treatment for surgery has risen since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417469","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Referral to treatment waiting times data, which measure waiting times from referral to the start of consultant-led treatment for non-urgent conditions, does not distinguish between patients waiting for surgery and patients waiting for other types of consultant-led treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At the end of July 2015 there were 232,424 people waiting more than 18 weeks to start consultant led treatment compared to 209,411 in May 2010, an increase of 23,013 people. The main driver for this increase is the growth in demand for elective care over the period due to a range of demographic and other factors such as technological changes in the provision of care. However, the number of people waiting more than 18 weeks as a proportion of the total number of people waiting to start consultant-led treatment is lower in July 2015 than in May 2010, 7.1% of the total waiting list compared to 8.1% in May 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The average median waiting times for all patients who started treatment and that involved an admission during July 2015 was 9.1 weeks compared to 8.4 weeks in May 2010. The time waited for those patients who had waited more than 18 weeks to start treatment is not separately identified.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417469/answer",,,,,"HL2064","2015-09-16T13:52:13.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417469/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417469/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Surgery: Waiting Lists","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government by how much waiting times have risen since May 2010 for those patients who are not treated for common forms of surgery within the 18 weeks waiting limit.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417470","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-22","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region and has pledged over £1 billion, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. The UK has allocated £519 million to support refugees in the region and vulnerable host communities to date, including £279 million in Lebanon and £183 million in Jordan. Whilst addressing the immediate needs of refugees and vulnerable members of host communities, UK aid is also supporting their longer term resilience and stability through funding to Lebanese and Jordanian municipalities for the running of essential public services, such as education.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK is also supporting the No Lost Generation Initiative in support of Syrian children across the region and funding to UNICEF includes the construction and refurbishment of schools, the provision of school supplies, psycho-social support to children and incentives for Syrian teachers both in camps and in host communities. However, the decision to what extent Syrian teachers can be involved in the provision of education is determined by host Governments.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417470/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-22T13:49:27.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417470/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417470/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-08","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have for preventing the stagnation of Syrian refugees in external camps; and what assessment they have made of the case for involving Syrian teachers in education for both children and adults in such camps.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417471","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-23","<p>There was no partial embargo imposed in 2014 on military supplies and equipment for Israel. However, a review of licences in circulation at the outbreak of hostilities in July 2014 identified 12 export licences the Government would suspend, as a precautionary measure, in the event of a resumption of significant hostilities. The Government was concerned that in these circumstances it would be unable to clarify whether the export licensing criteria were being met. This was announced on 12 August 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The results of a further review were announced on 14 July 2015 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/review-of-export-licensing-procedures-for-israel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/review-of-export-licensing-procedures-for-israel</a>) and concluded that 11 months after the establishment of a ceasefire between Israel and Hamas, there was now sufficient information from a wide variety of sources to apply standard export licensing procedures using the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria without any additional measures such as the precautionary measure adopted in August 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The specific details of the review were not considered by the Cabinet. This is because export licensing policy is set by the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills. In setting this policy the Secretary of State always seeks and takes into account advice from other Cabinet colleagues, including the Foreign and Defence Secretaries.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417471/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-23T10:34:47.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417471/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417471/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Israel: Arms Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to what extent the partial embargo imposed in 2014 on military supplies and equipment for Israel has been lifted; what was the reason for this decision; and whether the matter was considered by the Cabinet.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417472","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>At the end of Quarter 1, payments of £163million have been made from the £1,033million Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) with the majority of spend not scheduled until Quarter 2 and 3. The National Security Council (NSC) agreed CSSF allocations at the start of the Financial Year, the details of which were made in the Written Ministerial Statement about the CSSF on 12 March 2015 by the then Minister for Government Policy in the Cabinet Office, my right hon. Friend the Member for West Dorset (Mr Letwin), which was repeated the same day in the House of Lords by Lord Wallace of Saltaire, (HLWS379).</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417472/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T12:10:59.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417472/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417472/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what payments have been made since the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund was established; and what is the planned destination of expenditure from that fund during the rest of this financial year.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417473","Home Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>People who have been granted five years’ humanitarian protection in the United Kingdom, including Syrian nationals admitted under the Vulnerable Persons Relocation (VPR) scheme, have permission to work and access to broadly the same rights, benefits, education and training as British nationals.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417473/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T15:36:46.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417473/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417473/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether adults in receipt of five-year humanitarian protection in the United Kingdom will be allowed to work; and what provision will be made for their education or training.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417474","Home Office","false","2015-09-30","<p>I apologise for the late reply to your question. This is due to the rapid pace of development of the EU response to the migration crisis currently facing the European Union, as demonstrated by the convening of a further extraordinary JHA Council meeting on 22 September.</p><p>The Luxembourg Presidency of the European Union convened the extraordinary meeting of the Justice and Home Affairs (JHA) Council on 14 September in Brussels in response to a joint request that My Right Honourable Friend the Home Secretary (Theresa May MP) made with the French and German Interior Ministers. A further extraordinary meeting of the JHA Council was held on 22 September. The Home Secretary attended both meetings on behalf of the United Kingdom.</p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Home Secretary will write to the Chairman of the European Scrutiny Committee, and to his counterpart in the European Union Committee, setting out the key decisions taken, and the interventions that my Rt. Hon Friend made, at the Extraordinary JHA Councils that took place on 14 and 22 September. A copy of these letters will be placed in the House library. Additionally, the Commission’s Migration Package has been deposited for scrutiny by both Houses.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417474/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-30T16:05:21.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417474/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417474/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they plan to make to European Union ministers at the 14 September meeting on EU migration; and whether they plan to make representations on the issue of co-operation between EU member states, including those outside the Euro or Schengen areas.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417475","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK has allocated £500 million to support Syrian refugees in the region, the majority of who live in host communities. Our support has reached hundreds of thousands of people in Jordan, Lebanon, Turkey, Iraq and Egypt and helped host governments deal with the influx of refugees. As well as meeting immediate needs of refugees and vulnerable members of host communities, we are helping build the longer term resilience of refugees through funding to local municipalities for essential public services, such as education. Syrian refugees in Tunisia are being supported by UNHCR.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417475/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T12:02:34.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417475/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417475/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-08","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their policy on the treatment of Syrian refugees living outside refugee camps in Lebanon, Jordan, Turkey, and Tunisia.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417476","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","There have been no discussions in the Security Council or UN fora about the involvement of British troops in the ongoing Syria conflict.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417476/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T12:10:50.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417476/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417476/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had in the Security Council and other UN organisations about the involvement of British troops in Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL2072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417477","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>Consultation with any partners or tenants is a matter for the vendor of the building rather than the Education Funding Agency as purchasers.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417477/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:07:12.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417477/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417477/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-08","Education Funding Agency: Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Education Funding Agency did not consult all relevant partners when purchasing Spitfire House in Castle Vale, Birmingham.","true","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417478","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Education Funding Agency first visited the property and began negotiations on 8 July 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The purchase price was £1,500,000 (exclusive of VAT).</p><p>The vendor, Birmingham Metropolitan College, received the purchase monies.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417478/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:05:47.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417478/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417478/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-08","Education Funding Agency: Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on what date the Education Funding Agency became involved in purchasing Spitfire House in Castle Vale, Birmingham; what price they paid for the building; and who received the purchase monies.","true","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417479","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Education Funding Agency (EFA) was not party to the original funding agreement with the European Regional Development Fund and therefore ensuring relevant consultation and compliance is a matter for the vendor rather than the purchaser.</p><p><br> EFA legal team confirmed that the title contained no caution or charge in respect of the European Regional Development Fund.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417479/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:07:40.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417479/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417479/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-08","Education Funding Agency: Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which Department is responsible for ensuring that the project regarding the change of ownership and function of Spitfire House in Castle Vale, Birmingham, complies with financial rules under the European Regional Development Fund.","true","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417480","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>The property was purchased subject to restrictions on title relating to community access. No restrictive covenants regarding community access have been removed or amended and therefore no consultation was necessary.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417480/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:06:59.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417480/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417480/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-08","Education Funding Agency: Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions took place, and with which organisations, about the proposal to lift the restrictive covenants regarding community access in respect of Spitfire House in Castle Vale, Birmingham.","true","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417481","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>All schools have a responsibility to provide a safe environment in which children can learn. Ofsted has completed a pre-registration inspection at this school and advised that this school is likely to meet all the independent school standards when it opens, including those relating to the welfare, health and safety of its pupils.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Trust is preparing a management plan so that the school will be able to operate independently from the other occupants in the premises.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The September 2015 pupil intake will be located on the second floor which is not co-habited by others.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417481/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T15:06:20.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417481/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417481/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-08","Education Funding Agency: Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what safeguarding arrangements are in place for the free school that will operate in part of Spitfire House in Castle Vale, Birmingham.","true","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417482","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-24","<p>The Homes and Communities Agency does not own or control Spitfire House and had no involvement in the decision of Birmingham Metropolitan College to sell the property to the Education Funding Agency. The Agency’s role is limited to determining whether a legal charge it holds over the building should be removed.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417482/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-24T15:56:19.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417482/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417482/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-08","Education Funding Agency: Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the role of the Homes and Communities Agency in respect of Spitfire House in Castle Vale, Birmingham, following a change of ownership.","true","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417483","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>Ministers are currently carefully considering the recommendations made in the review. The Government response will be published in the autumn.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417483/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T11:15:40.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417483/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417483/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-08","Independent Rural Proofing Implementation Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in implementing the recommendations of the Independent Rural Proofing Implementation Review; and when they expect to report fully on that progress.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL2079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417484","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417484/answer","HL2080 UKSA Reply.pdf","HL2080 UKSA Reply.pdf","UK Statistics Reply ","UK Statistics Reply ",,"2015-09-17T12:22:44.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417484/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417484/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-08","Government Departments: Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether all government departments have now adopted the Office for National Statistics rural-urban classification in their analyses of data and evidence.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL2080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417485","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-18","<p>My right hon. friend the Defence Secretary authorised this operation. The Attorney General was consulted in advance and advised that there would be a clear legal basis for action in international law.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417485/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T14:03:14.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417485/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417485/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-08","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what legal authority they obtained before conducting the drone attack in Syria that was announced on 7 September.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417486","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-18","<p>As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced to the House on 7 September, Reyaad Khan was killed in a precision air strike carried out in Raqqa on 21 August by an RAF remotely piloted air system. In addition to Reyaad Khan, two ISIL fighters were also killed.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417486/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T14:03:20.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417486/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417486/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-08","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people were killed during the drone strike on Raqqa on 21 August.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417487","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-18","<p>My right hon. Friend The Prime Minister confirmed in his statement to the House on 7 September that there were no civilian casualties resulting from the precision air strike in Raqqa on 21 August 2015.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417487/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T14:03:07.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417487/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417487/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-08","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any civilians were killed in the drone strike on Raqqa on 21 August.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417488","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-21","<p>As far as we are aware, there have not been any civilian casualties resulting from UK strikes against ISIL.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417488/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T15:08:05.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417488/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417488/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-08","Middle East: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the level of collateral damage from air strikes and drone strikes in the civilian areas in Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417489","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK strongly supports international and local efforts to seek a comprehensive political settlement in Syria, in particular the political process being taken forward by UN Special Envoy Staffan de Mistura. The UK is funding discussions between non-state actors representing key interest groups to encourage a Syrian national dialogue, as well as local level peace-building projects to mediate and mitigate local conflicts and to strengthen cohesion and moderate voices in these communities. The UK fully supports Prime Minister Abadi’s work to deliver the reforms and political reconciliation needed to persuade all of Iraq’s communities – Shias, Sunnis and Kurds – that they have a stake in Iraq’s future. In 2015/16 we will provide funding for a number of projects in Iraq designed to support community cohesion and encourage reconciliation, acceptance and tolerance between communities at a grass roots level. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has also deployed or reassigned 20 officers to help better understand and support the political process in Iraq, including efforts to reach out to members of the Sunni community.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417489/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T12:10:42.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417489/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417489/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Middle East: Peace Negotiations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have supported any peace or reconciliation efforts in Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417490","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>We have made no such assessment. However, a number of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant's senior leadership are assessed to be Iraqis who served within Saddam Hussein’s regime.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417490/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-18T12:10:31.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417490/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417490/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-08","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made, if any, of the number of people serving or training with Daesh in Syria and Iraq who were formerly soldiers or civil servants under Saddam Hussein.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417491","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The total cost of the investigation, into the disappearance of Madeleine McCann (Operation Grange), up until end of June 2015, is £10.1m. The Home Office has budgeted £2m for the investigation in 2015/16.</p><p>The Home Office funds this work from the Special Grant budget. The level of funding provided to the Metropolitan Police in relation to this investigation is reviewed regularly and will continue to be monitored.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417491/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T13:28:07.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417491/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417491/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Madeleine McCann","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what has been the cost to date of the investigation into the disappearance of Madeleine McCann, Operation Grange; what provision has been made for funding the operation in the future; and what criteria they are using to judge how long funding should continue.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL2087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417492","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>Sir John Chilcot is paid a fee of £790 for each day worked. His three Committee colleagues are paid £565 for each day they work. According to the Inquiry’s website, since the Inquiry began in 2009, remuneration for the Committee and its advisers totalled £1,565,700 up to the end of the last financial year.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417492/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T15:34:32.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417492/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417492/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-08","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much Sir John Chilcot has been paid in daily allowances and expenses since the establishment of the inquiry into the Iraq war.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL2088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417493","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p>Provision of interpretation and translation services across courts and tribunals is being explored in preparation for the end of the current contracts in October 2016. A competition to retender the contract is expected to be launched in due course.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417493/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T15:07:52.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417493/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417493/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Courts: Interpreters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what the timetable and process will be for reviewing, publishing and awarding the contract for the provision of court interpreters, when the current contract expires at the end of 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL2089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417494","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-22","<p /> <p>The UK Government opted into these Directives, on 22 October 2010 and on 8 March 2010 respectively, and in transposing them into domestic law undertook careful analysis of the state of the existing law and whether any new measures were required to ensure compliance. As a result of this assessment, in England and Wales transposition included several new legislative measures, subsequently approved by Parliament, and the Devolved Administrations made similar arrangements. A full transposition table was provided to the European Commission as is normal practice. As with all Directives, the Government keeps compliance under review.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417494/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-22T09:41:30.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417494/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417494/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-08","Rights of Accused","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the compatibility of the current United Kingdom law with the European Union Directives on the right to information in criminal proceedings, and on the right to interpretation and translation in criminal proceedings.","false","Biography information for Baroness Coussins",,"Baroness Coussins","HL2090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417495","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government does not collate centrally information in respect of the cost of the former Police Authorities or of the Offices of the Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs).</p><p>Under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011, it is the responsibility of PCCs to determine how each police area’s funding settlement is allocated, including setting the police force budget and the running of the PCC’s office.</p><p>The 2011 Act specifies that PCCs must publish key information as prescribed by the Secretary of State. The Elected Local Policing Bodies (Specified Information) Order 2011 (and amended in 2012) sets out what information must be published: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/3050/contents/made" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/3050/contents/made</a></p><p>The publication of this information enables the local electorate to judge whether the PCC is making the best use of public money at the ballot box.</p><p>PCCs perform a completely different role from the old Police Authorities they replaced. PCCs are providing accountable, visible leadership, and making a real difference to policing locally.</p><p>The Home Affairs Select Committee recognised in their 2014 report that individual PCCs are providing greater clarity of leadership for policing in their areas, and are increasingly recognised for the strategic direction they are providing. In contrast, Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary found, in 2010, that only four of the 22 police authorities inspected were judged to have performed well in two of their primary functions: setting strategic direction and ensuring value for money.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417495/answer","SI - 2011 - No 3050 - Police, England and Wales - Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011.pdf","SI - 2011 - No 3050 - Police, England and Wales - Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011.pdf","The Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011 ","The Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011 ",,"2015-09-16T14:03:14.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417495/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417495/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Police and Crime Commissioners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the cost of the Office of the Police and Crime Commissioner for each police area in England and Wales for each year between 2012 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord German",,"Lord German","HL2091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417496","Home Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Home Office does not hold information on the number of eligible electors in each police area in 2011.</p><p>For 2012, when the first elections for Police and Crime Commissioner took place across England and Wales, the Home Office does not hold verified data. However, this information should be available directly from local authorities via the relevant Police Area Returning Officer (PARO).</p><p>For 2013, the Home Office does not hold this data.</p><p>For 2014, the number of eligible electors in the two police areas where by-elections took place were: West Midlands: 1,974,518; South Yorkshire: 1,010,599. This information has been verified by the relevant PARO for each police area. The Home Office does not hold data for eligible electors for the remainder of police force areas.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417496/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T14:51:04.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417496/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417496/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Police and Crime Commissioners: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, for each year between 2011 and 2014, how many people were eligible in each police area to take part in elections for police and crime commissioners in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord German",,"Lord German","HL2092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417497","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government does not collate centrally information in respect of the cost of the former Police Authorities or of the Offices of the Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs).</p><p>Under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011, it is the responsibility of PCCs to determine how each police area’s funding settlement is allocated, including setting the police force budget and the running of the PCC’s office.</p><p>The 2011 Act specifies that PCCs must publish key information as prescribed by the Secretary of State. The Elected Local Policing Bodies (Specified Information) Order 2011 (and amended in 2012) sets out what information must be published: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/3050/contents/made" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/3050/contents/made</a></p><p>The publication of this information enables the local electorate to judge whether the PCC is making the best use of public money at the ballot box.</p><p>PCCs perform a completely different role from the old Police Authorities they replaced. PCCs are providing accountable, visible leadership, and making a real difference to policing locally.</p><p>The Home Affairs Select Committee recognised in their 2014 report that individual PCCs are providing greater clarity of leadership for policing in their areas, and are increasingly recognised for the strategic direction they are providing. In contrast, Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary found, in 2010, that only four of the 22 police authorities inspected were judged to have performed well in two of their primary functions: setting strategic direction and ensuring value for money.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417497/answer","SI - 2011 - No 3050 - Police, England and Wales - Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011.pdf","SI - 2011 - No 3050 - Police, England and Wales - Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011.pdf","SI -The Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011","SI -The Elected Local Policing Bodies - Order 2011",,"2015-09-17T12:22:17.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417497/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417497/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Police Authorities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the cost of each police authority in England and Wales in 2011–12.","false","Biography information for Lord German",,"Lord German","HL2093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417498","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>We remain committed to these reforms and will provide an update on implementation plans once the Spending Review has been completed.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417498/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T11:20:58.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417498/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417498/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Death Certificates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in implementing the recommendations of the Shipman Inquiry in order to introduce procedures to reform the death certificate system and to allay the fears of those who have lost their loved ones.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL2094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417499","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The review of local government archaeology services usefully highlighted the imperative of ensuring that local planning authorities have the historic environment information and expertise they need to help deliver sustainable development. Historic England is currently working with the Historic Environment Forum to develop sector-led ideas for new approaches to managing change in the historic environment that make the best use of local government resources and reduce burdens.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417499/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T16:22:54.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417499/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417499/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-08","Archaeology","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to publish the review of local government archaeology services by John Howell MP and Lord Redesdale, which was commissioned in October 2013 by the Minister for Culture, Communication and Creative Industries, Mr Ed Vaizey MP; and when they plan to announce their response.","false","Biography information for Lord Renfrew of Kaimsthorn",,"Lord Renfrew of Kaimsthorn","HL2095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417500","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-30","<p>The Government welcomes the work of companies such as Agri-Broadband who are providing superfast broadband services to rural communities.</p><p><br>We recognise that a range of solutions will be required to reach those in the hardest to reach areas. That is why the Government has invested up to £8 million to support seven pilot projects to explore ways to extend superfast broadband beyond 95% of UK premises, with technologies such as satellite and wireless and using alternative financing models.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417500/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-30T15:28:52.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417500/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417500/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-08","Broadband","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the invention by Agri-Broadband which has enabled broadband speed to be increased from 1 Mbps to 45 Mbps; and whether such an invention could contribute to equipping rural areas with superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417501","Home Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>There are currently no plans to authorise the sale of such ammunition in the United Kingdom. However, any ammunition which is armour-piercing is prohibited under section 5 of the Firearms Act 1968.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417501/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-15T14:37:42.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417501/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417501/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to authorise the sale in the United Kingdom of anti-drone ammunition for use in 12-gauge shotguns.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417502","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Electronic cigarettes have the potential to help smokers quit smoking, and the evidence indicates that, for smokers, they are less harmful to health than cigarettes. However, they are not risk free, and therefore they should only be used as a means to help smokers quit. The best thing a smoker can do is to quit completely.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For those that cannot stop using nicotine completely, or need help not to relapse, National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance already promotes the use of harm reduction strategies using a range of nicotine replacement therapies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any smoker wanting to quit, with or without the help of an e-cigarette, is advised to seek expert advice and support from their local stop smoking service. Smokers using the personalised support offered by stop smoking services are four times more likely to stop smoking and quit for good.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All smokers, including those who want to use e-cigarettes to help them quit, can sign up to Stoptober to receive additional help and support.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417502/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T15:26:20.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417502/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417502/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Electronic Cigarettes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to promote the use of e-cigarettes as a replacement for smoking tobacco.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417504","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Injured service men and women are able to access National Health Service facilities and treatments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All secondary acute and community care is currently provided by the NHS for those serving in the Armed Forces and primary care is provided by the Ministry of Defence’s Defence Medical Services (DMS). In some cases, injured serving personnel can be granted temporary registration with an NHS general practitioner for primary care if authorised by the DMS for up to two years where it is in the best interest of the patient’s care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any patient is free to choose to fund privately a healthcare procedure, but as a result will generally be required to pay all costs associated with that procedure.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417504/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T14:02:08.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417504/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417504/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-08","Health Services: Armed Forces","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have, if any, to provide injured service men and women with full access to NHS facilities and treatments; and whether any such provision would be made for individuals who have access to private treatment.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417505","Home Office","false","2015-09-24","<p>None of the economists in question are employed in any capacity to advise the Home Office.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417505/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-24T13:15:11.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417505/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417505/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-08","Economic Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any of the economists who wrote a letter to <i>The Times</i>, published on 18 August, are employed in any capacity to advise Government departments or are serving on any executive or non-executive bodies.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417506","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2015-09-21","<p>At the end of the 2009-10 session, of those peers eligible to take part in the work of the House of Lords there were 211 Labour members, 185 Conservative members and 72 Liberal Democrat members – meaning there were 46 more peers sitting on the benches of the two largest political parties in opposition than there were peers on the Government benches.</p><p> </p><p>As of 18 September, of those peers eligible to take part in the work of the House of Lords there are 223 Conservative members, 211 Labour members and 101 Liberal Democrat members – meaning there are 89 more peers sitting on the benches of the two largest political parties in opposition than there are peers on the Government benches.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417506/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-21T14:48:46.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417506/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417506/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2015-09-08","House of Lords Composition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by the Leader of the House on 7 September (HL Deb, col 1212), whether they will publish the statistics on which they base the statement that the Government face a combined opposition of 80 Peers, which is twice the size faced by the last Labour Government.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL2102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417507","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government does not collect statistics on what proportion of lost property is recovered from airports. This is a matter for the airports concerned.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417507/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T14:03:47.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417507/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417507/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-08","Airports: Lost Property","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of lost property is recovered from (1) Heathrow airport, (2) Manchester airport, (3) Liverpool airport, (4) Gatwick airport, and (5) Glasgow airport.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL2103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417508","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government does not hold information on the lost property arrangements of individual airports or any revenue that they collect as a result. However it is usual practice for items to be retained for a minimum of 90 days and then either auctioned, donated or, where they may be deemed hazardous, to be disposed of in a suitable manner.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417508/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T14:03:36.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417508/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417508/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-08","Airports: Lost Property","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what happens to the lost property that is not recovered at (1) Heathrow airport, (2) Manchester airport, (3) Liverpool airport, (4) Gatwick airport, and (5) Glasgow airport; and what revenue, if any, property that is not recovered raises for each airport.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL2104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417509","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>The table below sets out monitoring arrangements and outcomes for the 12 hen harrier nesting attempts in England in 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Nest</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Landowner</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Nest monitored by</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Notes</strong></p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>Private landowner</p></td><td><p>Local raptor workers</p></td><td><p>Chicks Fledged</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>Private landowner</p></td><td><p>Local raptor workers</p></td><td><p>Chicks Fledged</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>Natural England</p></td><td><p>Natural England</p></td><td><p>Chicks Fledged</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>Forestry Commission</p></td><td><p>Forestry Commission/</p><p>RSPB/Natural England</p></td><td><p>Chicks Fledged</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>Forestry Commission</p></td><td><p>Forestry Commission/</p><p>RSPB/Natural England</p></td><td><p>Chicks Fledged</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>United Utilities</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Chicks Fledged</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>United Utilities</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Nest failed</p></td><td><p>Male disappeared</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>United Utilities</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Nest failed</p></td><td><p>Male disappeared</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>United Utilities</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Nest failed</p></td><td><p>Male disappeared</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>United Utilities</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Nest failed</p></td><td><p>Male disappeared</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>United Utilities</p><p> </p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Nest failed</p></td><td><p>Predation</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>RSPB</p></td><td><p>Nest failed</p></td><td><p>Male disappeared</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417509/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T16:25:25.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417509/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417509/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-08","Birds of Prey: Conservation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, of the 12 hen harrier nesting attempts in England in 2015, how many of (1) the six failed nests, and (2) the six successful nests, were on land in an area where the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds had primary control over access to the nests.","false","Biography information for Viscount Ridley",,"Viscount Ridley","HL2105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417510","Attorney General","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does hold records identifying the number of defendants prosecuted, at the Crown Court, where the Principal Offence has been identified as homicide. However, it does not maintain a separate central record of defendants prosecuted specifically for murder or of cases where the issue of loss of control has been raised as a live issue. This information could only be obtained by examining CPS case files, which would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417510/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T16:33:04.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417510/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417510/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-09-08","Homicide: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, in how many murder trials the issue of the loss of control of the defendant was raised in each year since 2010; and if he will estimate in how many such trials (a) female and (b) male defendants were not convicted of murder on those grounds.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417511","Attorney General","false","2015-09-11","<p>Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) records show that, between 1st April 2009 and 10 September 2015, there have been 114 cases, recorded as assisted suicide or euthanasia, referred by the Police. 24 of these cases were later withdrawn by the police.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CPS central record cannot be filtered to identify how many referrals were received in each year. This information could only be obtained by manually examining CPS case files, which would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417511/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T13:10:52.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417511/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417511/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-09-08","Euthanasia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, in how many cases of assisted suicide the Crown Prosecution Service has received files in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","9398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417512","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>Information on apprenticeship participation by Level of study is published in Table 5 and Table 19 of a Statistical First Release (SFR):</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>An Intermediate Level Apprenticeship (Level 2) is considered equivalent to five GCSEs.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417512/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T12:15:14.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417512/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417512/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Apprentices: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the current number of intermediary qualification apprenticeships offering qualifications equivalent to five GCSE passes.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","9449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417513","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>Details on entry routes onto Apprenticeships can be found in the Apprenticeships Evaluation: Learners survey report online. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387662/bis-14-1208-Apprenticeships-Evaluation-Learners-December-2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387662/bis-14-1208-Apprenticeships-Evaluation-Learners-December-2014.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><br> In 2013/14, two thirds (64%) of apprentices worked for their employer before starting their apprenticeship. This has decreased since 2012/13 when it was 68%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417513/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T12:13:41.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417513/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417513/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of people currently enrolled on apprenticeships who were employed by the same organisation prior to the apprenticeship.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","9450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417514","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>This Government made available for the first time, non means tested loans to cover part time tuition fees. We have also extended student support for people who already have a degree to study for another in engineering, technology and computer science. We are also investing in higher level and degree apprenticeships - apprenticeships offer people an alternative to university as a path into skilled employment.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417514/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T14:28:14.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417514/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417514/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Higher Education: Part-time Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to support students in part-time higher education.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","9358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417515","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-05","<p>We have relaxed the rules for those wishing to retrain through part time study in some selected courses in science, technology and engineering courses, and in 2012 introduced tuition fee loans to help part time students finance their studies. In addition, we are also investing in higher level and degree apprenticeships. To support employer investment we have announced the introduction of an apprenticeship levy, enabling employers to choose and pay for apprenticeship training, including at higher level. A consultation on its implementation was launched on 21 August 2015.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417515/answer",,,,,,"2015-10-05T12:14:27.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417515/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417515/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Higher Education: Part-time Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to encourage employers to invest in part-time courses in higher education.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","9359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417516","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>An assessment of trends in entry to part-time higher education courses at different types of Higher Education provider was included in the Higher Education Funding Council for England’s report “Higher education in England 2014: Analysis of latest shifts and trends”. The report is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/hefce/content/heinengland/2014report/HEinEngland_2014.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/hefce/content/heinengland/2014report/HEinEngland_2014.pdf</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417516/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T14:27:34.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417516/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417516/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Higher Education: Part-time Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the reasons for changes in the number of students enrolling in part-time higher education courses in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","9360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417517","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-14","<p>All Local Enterprise Partnerships have higher education representation on their Boards and in preparing their Strategic Economic Plans consider and prioritise the most effective skills interventions for their areas, taking account of the needs of the local businesses and people.</p><p>To support part-time study, we have relaxed the rules for those wishing to retrain in some selected courses in science, technology and engineering, and in 2012 introduced tuition fee loans to help part time students finance their studies.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417517/answer",,,,,,"2015-10-14T16:08:49.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417517/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417517/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Higher Education: Part-time Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to support part-time higher education courses through Local Enterprise Partnerships.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","9357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417518","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>The National Careers Service provides careers information, advice and guidance to anyone aged 13 and over via their website and telephone service. Face-to-face guidance for adults aged 19 and over is also provided (aged 18 if individuals are in custody or customers of Jobcentre Plus).</p><p> </p><p>The Skills Funding Agency carried out an impact assessment on the current priority groups in 2012. These priority groups include adults who are unemployed, people with disabilities, adults facing redundancy or newly redundant, individuals distant from the labour market, in custody or have low skills. We believe that these groups are sufficient to provide a high quality service to all customers, including those from ethnic minorities groups, and that there is no need for further assessment.</p><p> </p><p>Between October 2014 and June 2015, around 24% of National Careers Service customers were from an ethnic minority background.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417518/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T14:26:51.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417518/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417518/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Vocational Guidance: Minority Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of treating ethnic minority groups as a priority by the National Careers Service.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","9368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417519","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-13","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Government’s priorities in Europe.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417519/answer",,,,,,"2015-10-13T13:15:52.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417519/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417519/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many officials in his Department are engaged in research into the effects of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417520","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-25","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. My Rt hon Friend he Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills regularly meets with a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe. Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417520/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-25T08:36:40.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417520/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417520/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which external organisations he has met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many times he has met each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417521","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. Officials regularly meet with a range of external organisations to discuss the Government's objectives in Europe.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417521/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T16:57:48.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417521/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417521/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which external organisations officials in his Department have met to discuss the consequences of the UK leaving the EU in each of the last three years; and how many meetings such officials have had with each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417522","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government publishes comprehensive information about export licences granted and refused on gov.uk. The most recently published information covers the period until 31 March 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since April 2010 782 licences have been granted for export of military goods and technology to Saudi Arabia. The end-use of each such licence could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417522/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T09:08:00.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417522/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417522/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many export licences have been issued for export defence material to Saudi Arabia since April 2010; and for what purpose each such licence was so issued.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417523","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>In 2014, following restrictions imposed by Russia, total food, feed and drink exports to Russia totalled £93.7million, a 29.3 per cent drop compared to 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Exports to Russia in these sectors accounted for around one per cent of the UK’s total global exports in these sectors, which amounted to £18.8 billion in 2014. We estimate that the total number of exports to Russia in these sectors had fallen by £39 million.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ban on cleaning products was announced on 25 August 2015. It is too early to see any impact on UK exporters, but we will continue to monitor the situation.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417523/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T08:58:34.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417523/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417523/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Exports: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect on UK exporters of recently imposed Russian restrictions on the sale of food and cleaning products; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417524","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>All of the Grand Challenges relate either to the Eight Great Technologies and/or to objectives published in the Science and Innovation Strategy December 2014.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417524/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T10:22:24.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417524/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417524/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the relationship is between the priorities of the Grand Challenges and the Eight Great Technologies programmes.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417525","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The final figure on the number of Growth Vouchers issued is available now. This was provided in the response to Written Question UIN 9284. The final figure is 19,713.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417525/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-14T08:57:05.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417525/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417525/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the comments made by a spokesperson for his Department as reported in The Guardian on 16 August 2015, when the final figure on the number of Growth Vouchers issued will be available.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417526","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>Neither ministers nor officials from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills have issued any guidance to Research Councils on grant funding application deadlines since May 2015.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417526/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T10:18:23.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417526/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417526/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Research Councils: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what guidance he has issued to the Research Councils on deadlines for grant funding applications since May 2015; and what effect the forthcoming Spending Review has had on that guidance.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417527","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>Neither ministers nor officials from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills have had any recent discussions with Research Councils on grant funding application deadlines. Deadlines for individual funding calls are a matter for the Research Councils or other funding partners where involved.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417527/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T10:16:57.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417527/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417527/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Research Councils: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions Ministers and officials of his Department have had with the Research Councils on grant funding application deadlines.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417528","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Department will not be publishing the McKinsey work on the grounds that to do so would be likely to reduce the Government’s ability to protect the policy-making process and maintain the delivery of effective Government.</p><p>The Department does not hold centrally a record of all external reports, or policy evaluations, that have been carried out by external organisations for the Department and its Agencies. To produce such a list dating back to May 2010/ financial year 2010-11 respectively would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417528/answer",,,,,"9242","2015-09-17T09:29:55.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417528/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417528/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Non-departmental Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish the report commissioned by his Department from McKinsey on the executive agencies and bodies funded by his Department; and what other external reports he has commissioned on such agencies and bodies since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417529","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p /> <p>In April 2014 BIS published the findings of the Triennial Review of the Research Councils, which examined their form, function and governance. In December 2014 the Government commissioned Sir Paul Nurse to examine how Research Councils can evolve to support research in the most effective ways.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417529/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T10:16:16.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417529/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417529/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Research Councils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what external reviews or research he has commissioned on the future of the Research Councils.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417530","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has replied to the hon Members.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417530/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-17T13:31:20.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417530/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417530/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Members for Ashfield and Streatham dated 15 June 2015 regarding women executives on company boards.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","9619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417531","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Joint Information Systems Committee (JISC) is a sector owned charity, independent of Government and oversees the provision of e-infrastructure in higher education.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills through HEFCE and in conjunction with other sector funders (Scottish Funding Council, Higher Education Funding Council Wales, Department for Employment and Learning Northern Ireland) provides funding on an annual basis to JISC in support of the development, maintenance, and support of shared e-infrastructure services for the higher education sector. In 2015-16 HEFCE has provided JISC with £21 million in core funding and £19 million in capital funding.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417531/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T12:16:45.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417531/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417531/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Higher Education: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that (a) a comprehensive set of shared e-infrastructure services and (b) funding for such services are provided for the higher education sector.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417532","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Office for National Statistics (ONS) compiles statistics of low pay from the Annual Survey of Hours and Earning (ASHE). However, the ASHE sample size is too small to give reliable estimates of low pay at the constituency level. Breakdowns of low pay at the regional level are available here – <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/ashe/low-pay/april-2014/stb-2014-low-pay-estimates.html" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/ashe/low-pay/april-2014/stb-2014-low-pay-estimates.html</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417532/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T13:13:46.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417532/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417532/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Low Pay: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of jobs in each Scottish parliamentary constituency have an hourly pay below the Living Wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","9647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417533","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills is currently considering who should Chair the Review and who should assist them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The proposed Terms of Reference has been drafted in consultation with relevant stakeholders, including the ticketing and event industries, and will be finalised by the Chair to the Review.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417533/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-16T13:15:34.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417533/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417533/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-08","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, who was consulted in deciding on the personnel and terms of reference of a review into the secondary ticketing market; and how such consultees were selected.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","9629"
